-------------------------------------------------------------------Create Ros Worspace---------------------------------------------------------
1)create a folder FolderName with a subfolder src
2)open a terminal inside FolderName
3)catkin_make
4)source devel/setup.bash
-----------------------------------------------------------------Create a Packages folder------------------------------------------------------
1)cd src # go inside the src folder of the ros workspace
2)catkin_create_pkg <package_name> [depend1] [depend2] [depend3]#create pack with dependencies(standart dependencies are std_msgs rospy roscpp)
3) make sure to fill the package.xml and the CmakeLists.txt

NB: std_msgs     is a package which allows me to use the String type for message
    rospy        is a pure Python client library for ROS
---------------------------------------------------------------Writing a Message---------------------------------------------------------------
1)create an another package who will contains only the custum message The costume message will have .msg as extension
2)rosmsg show Package_name/MessageFile
---------------------------------------------------------------Writing the publisching node----------------------------------------------------
1)roscd Package_Name
2)mkdir scripts #inside the scripts folder i will put all my python scripts
3)cd scripts
4) write the puthon file.py
5) chmod +x talker.py  #make the file.py executable
6)catkin_install_python(PROGRAMS scripts/file.py DESTINATION ${CATKIN_PACKAGE_BIN_DESTINATION}) #add to the CMakeLists.txt
---------------------------------------------------------------------Build The Nodes-----------------------------------------------------------
1)cd Ros_ws
2)catkin_make
----------------------------------------------------------------------Running Nodes------------------------------------------------------------
1)open a new terminal and type roscore
2)inside ros_ws , source ./devel/setup.bash
3)
$ rosrun beginner_tutorials talker      (C++)
$ rosrun beginner_tutorials talker.py   (Python) 

